        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3417156591" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2781528073090497817">I advise you to not to have high expectations with this one, It&apos;s what you expect from a book titled like this. I loved the characters, felt bad for Nelly, and his embarrassing attempts that made me screech a little hoping he&apos;d stop being manipulative &amp; desperate. <br/><br/>For me, the character development is barely there, nothing new with Nelson or the basic second character that was very very forgettable for me.<br/><br/>Jason is the only one that developed perfectly, from an abused homophobe struggling with his</span>
  <span id="freeText2781528073090497817" style="display:none">I advise you to not to have high expectations with this one, It's what you expect from a book titled like this. I loved the characters, felt bad for Nelly, and his embarrassing attempts that made me screech a little hoping he'd stop being manipulative &amp; desperate. <br /><br />For me, the character development is barely there, nothing new with Nelson or the basic second character that was very very forgettable for me.<br /><br />Jason is the only one that developed perfectly, from an abused homophobe struggling with his sexuality to attending the first gay-straight alliance club meeting that'll publicize his sexuality to the whole school. He used to be so desperate to keep his sexuality hidden. <br /><br />It might sound like a cliche "I'm gay and scared" type of books that you can find everywhere on Wattpad but the year it was written, homosexuals were still unicorns to people. This is the perfect book to open people's eyes to the LGBTQ and HIV issues &amp; bring awareness to teenagers' struggles with their sexuality and internalized homophobia.<br /><br />The ending still looked rushed to me. 😐<br /><br />Regardless, this is a basic book that touches on a lot of major subjects, I don't get the bad reviews at all. I read it when I was bored. And well, I enjoyed it &amp; I feel like the matters in this book still applies, even now. Though I feel like there's no need for a sequel, I don't want to watch the author tear apart everything that was built here. Not gonna read it. I swear I'm not.<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br />I'm a little curious 😥 ok, maybe just a peek at the summary?</span>
